segments.text: Hoping that the battery is still up.
Let's see, and today is the 11th of June, Thursday, and I have the pleasure of being at Cala Vista and talking to Les Appelt, one of the most generous, thoughtful Aggies of all time.
Les, why did you attend A&M in the first place?
Why there?
Probably two reasons.
My brother had attended A&M and was a very devoted Aggie.
He was several years ahead of me.
And the other was probably largely economic.
At that time, Texas A&M was probably the least costly major college to attend.
My economics in my first two years at A&M were covered by the savings I made by staying out of college for two years.
I worked in a law office in Hollisville, and then due to some skills I had with watching a computer,
what they called at that time, which was simply a fast-moving air machine.
I computed acreages for the AAA program and I managed to save the sum of about six or seven hundred dollars in two years working.
Weldon, that's my brother, had done
volunteer and with that connection I was one of the very few freshmen that were given a job as a mess hall waiter.
That paid probably about twenty-five, twenty-six dollars a month.
fee for room and board and laundry was about $29 if I remember it at that time.
I don't recall just what I did in my freshman year, but I kept track of what I did my sophomore year and it cost me $350 to go to school in my sophomore year.
That's all the cash that I spent.
Plus the fact that my other dad would
write him a letter every week and enclose a criss-cross bill in it, which cost him spending money.
And really not even save money on that.
Now you entered as a freshman in the fall of...
I entered in the thirties.
Fall of 36, I guess.
Fall of 36.
Class of 37.
Graduated in 41.
So, okay.
You had visited the campus a number of times before enrolling.
Several times.
When you went to enroll, how did you get there?
On the train, the bus?
No, my folks took me, I think at that time,
a Dodge touring car and took me out there and loaded up all my few possessions in the back seat.
Yeah, now what were the, what did you take with you in terms of clothing and supplies?
You see at that time uniforms were furnished and so I took I suppose mostly underwear and maybe my toothbrush
toilet items, and, uh, safe to reserve.
You know, we traveled pretty light.
In fact, it was so inconsequential that I don't remember what it is.
Describe, if you can, how you were received.
How did you get in a dormitory, get in a unit, get enrolled?
Well, uh,
Memory's not really too good on that except that the dormitory assignment had been made and I knew where to go and where to unload.
And of course the freshmen were greeted by the sophomores who later began giving us instructions in campusology.
And there for a number of days, of course, there's no way a freshman would do anything right.
The fact that I had this job as a vessel caused some confusion among our sophomores.
which was Company E. And we were, luckily, we were in the brand new Baldwin Hall Dormitory, which was, fortunately for me, just directly across the street from those recent halls.
The fact that I had
But that exempted me from marching in with the outfit, which annoyed the sophomores more than.
So it turned out that about once a month, they would have a special session for me.
And at that time, we would come to known as ass tears.
So they'd all sit around.
reminded me of all my transgressions by having been so fortunate enough to have a job in Nassau.
And to show you how far the university progressed, the first two ramps in Walton Hall, A and B, were reserved for football teams.
And that was in the years when we had John Kimbrough, Ralph
So we got, all the freshmen got to know a lot of football players real good.
And I think they stayed in there my freshman, sophomore year, and then I think they got some other facilities as well.
But there was a whole lot different from the facilities we now have for our athletes.
Can you describe a typical
dormitory room at that time.
How was it furnished?
How big was it?
What did y'all have in it?
Typical there was the two rooms with a shower and a bath.
The lavatory was in the room.
So it was just basically the shower.
The floors were
concrete.
It had a special texture on it.
The room wall was just plastered and painted and there was a double bunk beds in each room.
So each room had two people.
size of the room and I'd say there was room for rainbows.
I said we could have two desks and I'd say the room was about 10, about 12.
So no rug, no curtains?
Not really.
We brought in anything like that.
We let them do that ourselves.
Usually we had a
Describe the campus physically when you arrived.
What was there?
It felt like this.
There was quite a bit of space between what's now known as the Jack Wayne's building and the old main building.
The library was there.
They had a true library in that main building across the street from what's now the ladies' dormitory.
was a building that was used in the animal husbandry department.
Possibly for study and demonstration.
It had some lots there and they stored hay in it and they had mangers there where they feed these animals.
I remember that very, very, very well because
Shortly after all the freshmen came in, I think maybe a day or two before actually school started, they aired all the freshmen out.
Describe airing out the freshmen.
Airing out the freshmen was just telling them
Well, they just literally chased you out of your room and posted sophomores there to keep you from coming back in.
And then all the sophomores, all the campers started hunting down the freshmen.
And they caught most of them.
And they had long sessions with them.

usually with the freshman ending up being accused of being uncooperative or sassy or whatever in order to be assessed the punishments all the way from using the board on them to push-ups and miscellaneous other indignities.
I had
I noticed this building I was picking up that Adam Huckabee had.
So when they aired me out, I took a certain Kutcher's Roof and beat it down there at high speed.
I spent the night in one of the manors with a nice soft hay cushion under me.
And actually, even though all the Huckabee's were around, I actually fell asleep.
The sophomore did come through there, but I pulled a bunch of hay over me.
And I survived that night very well.
I still remember that building.
But right now, I think the building is probably the Teague building was on top of that site.
those big open areas on the east side of the campus that now are the golf course and the bonfire area, what were those used for drill fields then?
Well, not so much were used.
The drill field that was used most was the one between the library and the Jack Williams Library.
That was used drill field there.
And that would have been just over to the north of the
where these animal husbandry small buildings were.
The area where the golf course is and on both sides of the road leading into the main building were used for various sundry military science projects.
The engineers used them largely in mapping.
We'd do plane table mapping.
We'd do lots of engineering activities, demonstrations on bridge building and road building and also on beam missions.
But that area was reserved for military instruction.
How were freshmen treated in general?
Well, the junior seniors treated freshmen quite well, but they can't have their hands washed because they saw to it that sophomores treated freshmen with bomb leaves.
And any effort whatsoever for a freshman to exert a predominant attitude was wiped out.
I don't know any freshman that ever went through that area that didn't accept an inferior position.
I think gave all of us a little insight into negative psychology.
And you can't get over it.
How often was a board used?
Not near as often as recruited, but there was no really restriction.
And it was a fair sized piece of wood.
Yeah.
Some of them were shaved down baseball bats.
Did you ever get hit by a board when you hadn't done anything?
Oh, absolutely.
Normally, how many licks would there be?
Well, usually maybe an order of three to five.
And that connection brings up another thing.
The worst experience I had with the board was in my junior year.
There was a tradition that
when you got promoted and you got sergeant stripes, corporal stripes, whatever you got, that they tacked those on.
I was made a tech sergeant which was five stripes and they put those on and then three days later I was promoted to master sergeant.
My contention was that they could put one more stripe on.
The juniors and seniors had, I mean the seniors had, the seniors did this.
The seniors, in all their wisdom, said, no, we have to knock the five off.
And then put the six on.
So then, about three or four days, you add all that up, we had 16 licks from each of the seniors.
Most of them were pretty moderate teps, but there was a fifth-year senior named Ken Jalowski that was, if you please, a real chicken kid.
In fact, he was the one who finally found him guilty of stealing some yearbooks at the end of the semester and I think he cleared him out.
But anyway, he...
It didn't really take to me.
There was an obvious reason, because I guess he knew I detested him.
But at any rate, he made a fatal error.
He hit me low.
And as you know, I'm a pretty good sized guy.
And he was one of the shaved down baseball guys.
And so I culled it and they pulled my pants down and the shirt off.
I had stripes across my legs that missed the buttocks.
And so he had to permit me to pop in one.
To make a short story short, I damn near drove him down his hall.
And blood came in through his pants.
I still recall how satisfied I was about that whole deal.
These are the little things that would occur.
Now your outfit was E?
It was E-Engineers.
E-Engineers.
Now, I wasn't sure that I was going to come back the second year for the finances.
There was some doubt about the mess hall job.

I don't recall all the details, but I registered late, and they informed me of a new company, and instead of being Walton Hall, that company was in BG Hall, which was an old wood building adjacent to Walton Hall.
Down there was the Beauty Bell building.
And so we, uh, F Company, that was really a, really a heartbreaker for me at the time.
to take it out of the company.
It was just one of those things that happened and I couldn't do anything about it.
But it turned out that F Company had got some pretty good juniors and seniors at that time.
And unusually good bunches.
We had a strong bunch of sophomores.
So by the time I was a senior, F Company was back up in the corner, ramp, closest to the mess hall.
And I had been selected as, it happened to be Lieutenant Colonel of the Commanding Engineer Regiment.
So, F Company, really it was a company of high morale.
We won the intramural championship my senior year.
What did PG stand for?
You're saying the initials.
That's a good one.
I haven't heard that.
Did your outfits have nicknames?
E and F?
No, not really.
Like I've heard of Spider D and
Were they both engineering companies?
Yes, he was an engineer regiment.
Six companies.
Two battalions, three companies each.
Describe the routine of a typical Monday through Friday day.
Got up at what time, did what when.
Take me through the whole day.
I'm not real sure about the exact times, but there's
Getting up pretty damn early.
I'd say we'd be riding out somewhere around 6.30 or 7.00.
And of course I'd head over to the mess hall.
The units would form up in the street and march in.
I think the march in was probably somewhere between 7.00 to 7.14, probably.
Maybe 7.30.
The classes started at 8.00.
Probably about 7 or 15.
Eating didn't take a long time.
How did you eat?
You had a job and... Well, I ate in a hell of a hurry.
And I still have a bad habit.
I had a certain table and my normal meal time was less than five minutes.
We'd finish and then we'd gulp the food down.
One of the advantages of being in the mess hall, one of them I got so much trouble with, was the sophomore ward.
At that time, they had a deal that freshmen couldn't have dessert, which was known as kush.
This may have come up here before.
And being a waiter, see, unless they
I kept a soft mold and watched them see what I was doing after I finished surgery.
They correctly suspected that I was eating kush, because I certainly was.
And that's why they'd have their special sessions with me, just in case that they overlooked anything.
fairly correct in their surmises that I did need special attention.
Alright, so would you get over there early, work, would you go back to the dorm before your eight o'clock class?
Yeah, I'd hit the dorm, grab my books and run to eight o'clock class.
Incidentally, getting back to the aspect of how we got registered on, it was a riot.
They had sections, you know, and they
decide what you wanted to do, and then you had to go from one place to another to sign up.
And about half the time you got there, the section that you had chosen to fill in your schedule was full.
So then you had to revise your schedule and go chasing around until you found the section wasn't full.
And it was really a dogfight to get the classes you wanted at the time you wanted.
Of course, everyone

one of the Monday, Wednesday, and Friday classes, and finally is the Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday classes that were left and if you didn't get your schedule just right and get there in a hurry, you'd end up with some Saturday classes.
Nobody wants Saturday morning classes.
But a lot of us got, by the time my sophomore year was formed,
get the money to teach them, the money they need to provide.
But freshman, I had a bunch of Saturday classes.
Now, of course, kids can pre-register electronically.
And I'd say it's a damn good thing because with 40,000 students against the 4,000 or 5,000 that we had, our system would actually have disintegrated, total confusion.
All right, in this routine, you go to class.
What did you do if you didn't have a class, say, at 10 o'clock?
What did you do with that off hour?
Well, according to sophomore, you're supposed to come back and be available for details.
According to the way we did it, we went to the library or went to some other freshman's room where they went to Washington.
But we avoided getting back to the dormitory.
All right.
You'd come back.
Then I'd go to Vessel Street and got a class.
Right.
Then after lunch.
Brought another class door.
And when you didn't have classes in the afternoon, what did you do with your afternoons?
Run details by the upperclassmen or on certain rare occasions slip off somewhere and take a nap.
Where would you?
Take that now.
Well, I had a good deal going on.
I had a day voucher.
She was a person that was not in the military and lived off campus.
A friend of mine from my hometown that lived in a little house
The side of the tracks across the east or west of Northgate, it runs about three or four hundred yards from that on-trip.
And I'd go down to Northgate and go about a quarter mile to Waterbriar.
and work my way back up along the railroad track, coming to the back part of this, and go take a nap.
That's another thing that they were probably right about by giving me special attention.
Eating cushions, sitting up, taking naps.
Both very, very bad deals.
The routine of the military drills, when
When did those occur and where?
Well, we had military science classes and a lot of that occurred during that time.
Also, the sophomores were charged with training the freshmen and a lot of that would occur just before
formations, particularly the evening formations that had freshmen out there driving them on.
See, I missed that.
That was a sin that I was duly castigated for.
And I do kind of miss the new drill.
I never did really learn to drill well.
The head inspector is Colonel Adcock, and he told me
that I'd been selected to command the regiment, doing one consideration where they figured if I'd out front by myself, nobody would notice that I'd out of step.
We had a long lanky sophomore that had asked why.
At that time, we had squads and platoons, and squad right, squad left, and not the Army drill.
The Army drill came in during the time of the student.
And the freshman sophomore year, the squad left, squad right, you know.
And I was not the most skilled freshman, I believe.
But we suffered through that.
And really, then is what the, you know, you ate, you went back to your room, the freshman year, you studied.
And these, you didn't see this coming out of my eyes, making sure you studied.
If you weren't studying, you'd rather be sitting in your desk and looking for it.
Every now and then, freshmen are always tired.
They're always sleeping.
And so one of the great sins would be caught up to you after you head down on your own and sleep.
That usually ends up with appropriate punishment.
Let's see.
In your outfit, who were some special friends that you made?
Well, I still have friends in my outfit.
Lou Bates, Bryce Allen.
was out in West Texas, not too far from Loveland.
And what I say occasionally.
And another one of my very special friends is down near Hollisville, Leroy Johnston.
And any of the ones that you're fresh with me after, whenever you see them, they're special friends.
Those two I spent more time with since then than I have.
Describe some of the, you mentioned some of the athletes.
Who were the notable student, students on the campus then?
Was John Kimbrough a noticeable, did everybody know who he was?
Oh yeah, everybody knew who Kimbrough was.
I don't, I got, I don't think, I don't know.
